{"title_page": "PFC Slavia Sofia", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname    = PFC Slavia Sofia\n| image       = PFC Slavia Sofia.svg\n| image_size  = 200px\n| fullname    = Professional Football Club Slavia\n| nickname    = ''\u0411\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0435'' (The Whites)\n| founded     = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1913|4|10}}\n| ground      = [[Stadion Slavia]]\n| capacity    = 25,556\n| owner       = Mladen Mihalev\n| chairman    = Ventseslav Stefanov\n| mgrtitle    = Head coach\n| manager     = [[Zlatomir Zagor\u010di\u0107]] \n| league      = [[First Professional Football League|First League]]\n| season      = [[2018\u201319 First Professional Football League (Bulgaria)|2018\u201319]]\n| position    = First League, 8th\n| website     = http://www.pfcslavia.com/\n| pattern_la1 = _slavia_sf_19_20_h\n| pattern_b1  = _slavia_sf_19_20_h\n| pattern_ra1 = _slavia_sf_19_20_h\n| pattern_sh1 = _slavia_sf_19_20_h\n| pattern_so1 = \n| leftarm1    = FFFFFF\n| body1       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm1   = FFFFFF\n| shorts1     = FFFFFF\n| socks1      = FFFFFF\n| pattern_la2 = _temuco18a\n| pattern_b2  = _botevvratsa1819_3rd\n| pattern_ra2 = _temuco18a\n| pattern_sh2 = _botevvratsa1819_3rd\n| pattern_so2 = _whitetop\n| leftarm2    = 000000\n| body2       = 000000\n| rightarm2   = 000000\n| shorts2     = 000000\n| socks2      = 000000\n}}\n\n'''PFC Slavia Sofia''' ({{lang-bg|\u041f\u0424\u041a \u0421\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0438\u044f \u0421\u043e\u0444\u0438\u044f}}) is a Bulgarian professional [[association football]] club based in [[Sofia]], which currently competes in the top tier of the Bulgarian football league system, the [[First Professional Football League|First League]]. Slavia's home ground is the [[Slavia Stadium]] in [[Ovcha kupel]] with a capacity of 25,556. The team's colours are white and black. Established on 10 April 1913, Slavia is currently the oldest sports club in Sofia. \n\nDomestically, the club has won the [[Bulgarian Championship]] seven times and the [[Bulgarian Cup]] eight times. They have also been runners-up in the championship ten times and have reached the cup final on three additional occasions.\n\nAmong the team's international successes are a [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]] semi-final in 1967 and a quarter-final in 1981, as well as two consecutive [[Balkans Cup]] trophies in 1986 and 1988.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Slavia logo 2010.png|150px|thumb|right]]\nOn 10 April 1913, a group of young people living near a Russian Monument in [[Sofia]] and representatives of the local capital clubs '''pula''' and '''Razvitie''', in a coffee-house \u2013 Alabin str. in Sofia, decided to establish an [[corporation|incorporated]] sports club, the first organized sport club in Sofia.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0421\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0438\u044f \u0437\u0430\u043f\u043e\u0447\u0432\u0430 \u0441 \u0442\u043e\u043f\u043a\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0435\u043c|url=http://www.7sport.net/archive7ds/2008/04/10/forum/d5006_3.htm|date=10 April 2008|publisher=7sport.net|language=Bulgarian}}</ref> The new incorporated club has named Slavia. Dimitar Blagoev \u2013 Palio, a 21-year-old student, was elected as the first president of the club. As members of the first club administrative council were elected Emanuil Geshev, Ferdinand Mihaylov, Tsvyatko Velichkov, Georgi Grigorov and Todor Kalkandzhiev.\n[[File:Slavia logo 2012 13.png|150px|thumb|right]]\nA few days later, was elected the first football team of the club \u2013 Stefan Lalov, Ilia Georgiev, Emanuil Geshev, Todor Kalkandzhiev, Stefan Chumpalov, Dimitar Blagoev \u2013 Palio (all of them from Botev) and Pavel Grozdanov, Ferdinand Mihaylov, Boris Sharankov, Asen Bramchev, Dimitar Cvetkov (all of them from Razvitie). The first sport dresses of the club were white shirts and black shorts. Since 1924, the team has played with white shirts and white shorts and up to present days it is popular as the \"White pride\". On 11 August 1913, Slavia played its first match, against local club Savata, and won 1\u20130.\n\nAfter [[World War I]], Slavia began to become more successful. On 5 June 1928, the club won its first champion title, winning 4\u20130 in the final match against [[PFC Cherno More Varna|Vladislav Varna]]. Slavia won the title five more times until 1946, in [[1930 Bulgarian State Football Championship|1930]], [[1936 Bulgarian State Football Championship|1936]], [[1938\u201339 Bulgarian National Football Division|1938\u201339]], [[1941 Bulgarian State Football Championship|1941]] and [[1943 Bulgarian State Football Championship|1943]].\n\nSlavia won its first [[Bulgarian Cup]] in 1952. By winning the 1963 Bulgarian Cup Final, Slavia qualified for the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]], the club's first appearance in European competition. They were drawn against Hungarian club [[MTK Budapest FC|MTK Budapest]] in the first round. Slavia were eliminated from the competition 2\u20131 on aggregate. Its most important achievements in Europe during [[1966\u201367 European Cup Winners' Cup|1966\u201367 Cup Winners' Cup campaign]] when Slavia eliminated [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]], [[RC Strasbourg Alsace|Strasbourg]] and [[Servette FC|Servette]], before being eliminated by [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite news|title=Slavia Sports Club turns 100|url=http://bnr.bg/sites/en/Sport/Pages/100413Slavia100.aspx|date=10 April 2013|publisher=bnr.bg}}</ref> The team consisted of great players such as goalkeeper [[Simeon Simeonov (footballer born 1946)|Simeon Simeonov]], [[Ivan Davidov]], [[Aleksandar Shalamanov]], [[Dimitar Largov]], [[Dimitar Kostov]] and [[Aleksandar Vasilev (footballer, born 1936)|Aleksandar Vasilev]].\n\nIn 1969, Slavia was merged with [[PFC Lokomotiv Sofia|Lokomotiv Sofia]] under the name ZhSK Slavia. Two years later, the two clubs split again after a split was supported by 100,000 fans.\n\nIn the 1980\u201381 season, led by Chavdar Tsvetkov and [[Andrey Zhelyazkov]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Zhelyazkov salutes centurions Slavia Sofia|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=bul/news/newsid=1939084.html|date=10 April 2013|publisher=uefa.com}}</ref> Slavia reached the quarter-finals of the [[1980\u201381 European Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]] before losing 6\u20133 on aggregate to [[Feyenoord]]. In 1986, Slavia won [[Balkans Cup]], defeating Greek side [[Panionios F.C.|Panionios]] 5\u20133 on aggregate in the final. In 1988, Slavia won the Balkans Cup for the second time.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0421\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0438\u044f \u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0434\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u0411\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043a\u043b\u0443\u0431\u043d\u0430 \u043a\u0443\u043f\u0430|url=http://www.pfcslavia.com/pages.aspx?id=21|date=|publisher=pfcslavia.com|language=Bulgarian}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Stoyan Kotsev, the former Slavia midfielder, was appointed as the club's new manager. After finishing fourth in [[1994\u201395 A PFG|1995]], they went on to win the [[Bulgarian A Professional Football Group|A PFG]] title in [[1995\u201396 A PFG|1995\u201396]]. Slavia finished with five points more than second-placed [[PFC Levski Sofia|Levski Sofia]]. This marked Slavia's first Bulgarian title since 1943. In the 2010\u201311 season, Slavia reached the Bulgarian Cup final, defeating [[PFC Ludogorets Razgrad|Ludogorets Razgrad]], [[FC Etar 1924 Veliko Tarnovo|Etar 1924]], [[PSFC Chernomorets Burgas|Chernomorets Burgas]] and [[FC Pirin Blagoevgrad|Pirin Blagoevgrad]] ''en route''. However, they lost the final 1\u20130 to [[PFC CSKA Sofia|CSKA Sofia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Bulgarian Cup win ends CSKA Sofia drought|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=bul/news/newsid=1635022.html|date=25 May 2011|publisher=uefa.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Slavia won the Bulgarian Cup for the eight time in its history, defeating rivals Levski Sofia at the Vasil Levski National Stadium after a penalty shootout. This enabled the team to play in the [[2018-19 UEFA Europa League]] second qualifying round. In the second qualifying round, Slavia eliminated Finnish side [[FC Ilves]]. However, in the third qualifying round, they lost to [[Hajduk Split]] of Croatia, thus being eliminated.\n\n\n===League positions===\n<timeline>\nImageSize = width:1600 height:70\nPlotArea  = left:10 right:10 bottom:30 top:10\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod     = from:01/07/1948 till:01/07/2020\nScaleMajor = unit:year increment:2 start:1949\nColors =\n  id:bl1  value:rgb(0.5,0.8,0.5)\n  id:bl2  value:rgb(0.9,0.9,0.3)\n  id:rs  value:rgb(0.8,0.6,0.6)\n  id:rn  value:rgb(0.9,0.1,0.1)\n\nPlotData= \n  bar:Position width:16 color:white align:center\n  from:01/07/1948 till:01/07/1949  shift:(0,-4) text:4\n  from:01/07/1949 till:01/07/1950  shift:(0,-4) text:2\n  from:01/07/1948 till:01/07/1950  color:green  shift:(0,14)  text: \"[[Bulgarian A Football Group|A Group]]\"  \n  from:01/07/1950 till:01/07/1951  shift:(0,-4) text:1\n  from:01/07/1950 till:01/07/1951  color:white  shift:(0,14)  text: \"[[Bulgarian B Football Group|B Group]]\"\n  from:01/07/1951 till:01/07/1952  shift:(0,-4) text:8\n  from:01/07/1952 till:01/07/1953  shift:(0,-4) text:5\n  from:01/07/1953 till:01/07/1954  shift:(0,-4) text:2\n  from:01/07/1954 till:01/07/1955  shift:(0,-4) text:2\n  from:01/07/1955 till:01/07/1956  shift:(0,-4) text:4\n  from:01/07/1956 till:01/07/1957  shift:(0,-4) text:6\n  from:01/07/1957 till:01/07/1958  shift:(0,-4) text:5\n  from:01/07/1958 till:01/07/1959  shift:(0,-4) text:2\n  from:01/07/1959 till:01/07/1960  shift:(0,-4) text:4\n  from:01/07/1960 till:01/07/1961  shift:(0,-4) text:11\n  from:01/07/1961 till:01/07/1962  shift:(0,-4) text:5\n  from:01/07/1962 till:01/07/1963  shift:(0,-4) text:10\n  from:01/07/1963 till:01/07/1964  shift:(0,-4) text:3\n  from:01/07/1964 till:01/07/1965  shift:(0,-4) t